    <weatherForecast/>
    <avalancheActivity>
      <highlights>The danger of moist and wet avalanches will increase but remain within the current danger level.</highlights>
      <comment>Decrease in avalanche danger as the temperature drops. Early morning: The surface of the snowpack will freeze to form a strong crust and will hardly soften at all. In steep terrain there is a danger of falling on the hard snow surface. Crampons or ski Crampons are useful, especially on traverses and very smooth and hard slopes. &lt;br/> Until midday the weather will be partly cloudy in some localities. &lt;br/> In the afternoon the activity of moist and wet avalanches will only slowly increase. The near-surface layers of the snowpack can be released in isolated cases by winter sport participants in particular in extremely steep terrain. &lt;br/> In particular in starting zones where no previous releases have taken place and at the base of rock walls more small and, in isolated cases, medium-sized natural wet avalanches are possible. &lt;br/> The conditions are generally favourable for ski touring.</comment>
    </avalancheActivity>
    <snowpackStructure>
      <comment>The spring-like weather conditions gave rise to rapid settling of the snowpack. &lt;br/> This situation gave rise to moistening of the snowpack below approximately 2500 m. &lt;br/> The amount of snow is subject to significant local variations. &lt;br/> Below the tree line hardly any snow is lying on southeast and southwest facing slopes. &lt;br/> Especially on the colder slopes above the treeline, in the valley basins and headlands that have been less affected by stormy winds in recent weeks, there is excellent snow cover. &lt;br/> Weak layers exist in the snowpack in particular on steep shady slopes.</comment>
    </snowpackStructure>
    <travelAdvisory/>
    <tendency>
      <highlights>Only isolated small moist and wet avalanches are possible.</highlights>
      <tendencyType>steady</tendencyType>
